'''Dick Hafer''' (July 20, 1937 – July 5, 2003)<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Gizzi, John |year=2003 |title=Death of the "Comics Commando" |journal=Human Events |url=http://humanevents.com/2003/08/29/politics-2003brweek-of-september-1/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6QoBtDnM8?url=http://humanevents.com/2003/08/29/politics-2003brweek-of-september-1/ |archivedate=4 July 2014 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> was an American comics artist. He is best known for his [[Christian]] and [[conservative]] [[comics]] with strong political and anti-extramarital sexuality views.
Hafer wrote about 70 comics. Although he is known most for his controversial political comics, Hafer covered a wide variety of topics: from church life (''Church Chuckles''<ref>{{cite web|title=Church Chuckles|url=https://www.amazon.com/Church-Chuckles-Dick-Hafer-ebook/dp/B00AW4DL3W/ref=pd_sim_b_2|work=Amazon.com|accessdate=29 December 2013}}</ref>), to model railroads (''Sometimes You Gotta Compromise: A Light-Hearted Look at Model Railroading--And Model Railroaders''<ref>{{cite web|title=Sometimes You Gotta Compromise: A Light-Hearted Look at Model Railroading-- And Model Railroaders|url=https://www.amazon.com/Sometimes-Gotta-Compromise-Light-Hearted-Railroading--/dp/0890245649/ref=sr_1_2?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1388282539&sr=1-2|work=Amazon.com|accessdate=29 December 2013}}</ref>), to dog ownership (''So You Want a Dog: Questionable Answers to Your Questions About Doggie Ownership''<ref>{{cite web|title=So You Want a Dog: Questionable Answers to Your Questions About Doggie Ownership|url=https://www.amazon.com/You-Want-Dog-Questionable-Questions/dp/0944875947/ref=sr_1_14?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1388282531&sr=1-14|work=Amazon.com|accessdate=29 December 2013}}</ref>).
Hafer is best known for his conservative social and religious views. One of his most controversial comics was the 1986 anti-homosexual comic ''Homosexuality: Legitimate, Alternative Deathstyle''.<ref>[http://www.boingboing.net/2008/09/03/bizarre-antigay-comi.html Bizarre anti-gay comic book from 1980s] on [[Boing Boing]]</ref> One of his best selling works was ''I Know That We're a Throw-Away Society, but This is Ridiculous!'', an [[anti-abortion]] pamphlet published 1988. He also specifically targeted politicians of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]: he parodied [[Ted Kennedy]] in ''Every Family Has One: Little Black Sheep'' (1982), and [[Michael Dukakis]] in ''Magical Mike'' (1988).
